downsizing of the socialist welfare system and the return of the household as the unit of production and consumption redefined the boundaries between the public and private. This volume is the first to offer a multidisciplinary perspective that sets its gaze exclusively on processes at work in the everyday lives of families, and on the implications for gender and intergenerational relations. By focusing on families, this book shifts the spotlight from macro transformations of the renovation era, orchestrated by those in power, to micro-level transformations, experienced daily in households between husbands and wives, parents and children, grandparents and other family members.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aFamiliesxCongressesxEconomic aspectsxVietnam. 0aFamiliesxEconomic aspectszVietnamvCongresses. 0aFamily policyxCongressesxVietnam. 0aFamily policyzVietnamvCongresses. 0aSocial changexCongressesxVietnam. 0aSocial changezVietnamvCongresses. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Marriage & Family.2bisacsh1 aBarbieri, Magali, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBélanger, Danièle, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080477112240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804771122423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804771122.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles